const faqItems = [
  {
    question: "Why does heavy fuel oil need a centrifuge?",
    answer: "Heavy fuel oil (HFO) carries significantly higher contaminant loads than lighter fuels — including asphaltenes, catalyst fines, rust, and water. These contaminants cause injector damage, turbine blade erosion, and combustion chamber deposits. Filters clog rapidly with HFO and cannot remove water. A self-cleaning disc stack centrifuge handles HFO's high sludge loads continuously and automatically."
  },
  {
    question: "What is the capacity range of fuel oil centrifuge systems?",
    answer: "Dolphin Centrifuge fuel oil systems range from 12 GPM to 65 GPM on HFO at 30 cSt (pre-heated to 190°F). For heavier fuels at 700 cSt, capacities range from 3 to 20 GPM at 200°F. <a href='/contact-for-alfa-laval-centrifuges/'>Contact us</a> with your fuel grade and volume requirements for specific sizing."
  },
  {
    question: "Does fuel oil need to be heated before centrifuging?",
    answer: "Yes. Heavy fuel oil must be pre-heated to reduce viscosity for effective centrifugal separation — typically to 190–200°F depending on the fuel grade. All Dolphin Centrifuge fuel oil modules include electric or steam pre-heaters as standard equipment, along with duplex basket strainers and PLC controls."
  },
  {
    question: "Can a fuel oil centrifuge meet ISO 8217 fuel quality standards?",
    answer: "Yes. Disc stack centrifuges ensure fuel meets ISO 8217 and OEM specifications for solids, water, and ash content. Operating at over 6,000 Gs, the centrifuge removes particles, water, and sludge to levels well within turbine and engine manufacturer requirements — critical for warranty compliance and equipment longevity."
  }
];

